Giacomo Tesio wrote:
&gt; 
&gt; Probably none of these home made mime types will become IANA
&gt; registered standards.
&gt; 

Don&#39;t confuse &#39;registered&#39; with &#39;standardized&#39;.  The procedure for
registering a media type identifer, is a two-minute phone call which
will tell you either it&#39;s already taken, or you can have it.  The
purpose of this is simply to avoid collisions on the Web, i.e.
application/vnd.foo+xml should only refer to one media type, not a set
of media types from different vendors.

Obviously, this is not a concern on your Intranet, where there&#39;s no
danger that your outfit&#39;s application/vnd.foo+xml gets confused for some
other outfit&#39;s application/vnd.foo+xml.

Media type identifiers don&#39;t need to point to standardized media types,
to be registered.  Media type identifiers only need to be registered,
if they&#39;re to be used on the public Internet.

-Eric
